of living in Springfield...

131
00:09:05,144 --> 00:09:08,136
but they ain't even bothered to learn
themselves the language.

132
00:09:08,247 --> 00:09:11,808
- Yeah. Those are exactly my "sentimonies. "
- Yeah!

133
00:09:11,918 --> 00:09:16,480
Yeah, you said it, Barn.

134
00:09:24,196 --> 00:09:28,462
Make the protesters go away,
and I'll give you the entire bottle.

135
00:09:28,568 --> 00:09:31,662
Oh, thank you goodness.
My first customers in a week.

136
00:09:31,771 --> 00:09:33,864
It's hard to believe someone
so close to our family...

137
00:09:33,973 --> 00:09:35,873
could be an illegal alien.

138
00:09:35,975 --> 00:09:37,875
Alas, it is true.

139
00:09:37,977 --> 00:09:41,344
I came here shortly after
my graduation from Cal Tech...

140
00:09:41,447 --> 00:09:43,415
<i>Calcutta Technical Institute.</i>

141
00:09:43,516 --> 00:09:47,111
<i>As the top student
in my graduating class of seven million...</i>

142
00:09:47,219 --> 00:09:51,781
<i>- I was accepted for graduate
study in the United States.</i>

143
00:09:54,527 --> 00:09:57,621
Mmm.

144
00:09:57,730 --> 00:10:02,599
Wherever you go and whatever you do,
we will always love you.

145
00:10:02,702 --> 00:10:06,433
- Make us proud, Son.
- Never forget who you are.

146
00:10:06,539 --> 00:10:09,667
I won't, Mother.
And I won't forget you, Manjula.

147
00:10:09,775 --> 00:10:13,267
I'm so sorry our arranged marriage
will not come to pass.

148
00:10:13,379 --> 00:10:15,279
Farewell, my beloved.

149
00:10:15,381 --> 00:10:18,544
<i>I enrolled at
Springfield Heights Institute of Technology...</i>

150
00:10:18,651 --> 00:10:22,610
<i>under the tutelage
of the brilliant professor, John Frink.</i>

151
00:10:22,722 --> 00:10:26,681
Well, sure, the Frinkiac 7 looks impressive-
don't touch it-

152
00:10:26,792 --> 00:10:31,126
but I predict that within 100 years,
computers will be twice as powerful...

153
00:10:31,230 --> 00:10:33,255
10,000 times larger...

154
00:10:33,366 --> 00:10:37,962
and so expensive that only the five
richest kings of Europe will own them.

155
00:10:38,070 --> 00:10:40,129
Could it be used for dating?

156
00:10:40,239 --> 00:10:42,173
Well, theoretically, yes.

157
00:10:42,274 --> 00:10:47,177
But the computer matches would be so perfect
as to eliminate the thrill of romantic conquest.

158
00:10:49,281 --> 00:10:53,377
Nine glorious years later,
I completed my Ph. D. thesis.

159
00:10:53,486 --> 00:10:56,478
200,000 precisely ordered punch cards...

160
00:10:56,589 --> 00:10:59,820
comprising the world's very first
tic-tac-toe program.

161
00:10:59,925 --> 00:11:03,986
<i>- Only the top human players could beat it.
- Hey, what's this one for?</i>

162
00:11:04,096 --> 00:11:07,122
Oh!

163
00:11:07,233 --> 00:11:10,828
<i>So, Apu, why didn't you go back
to India when your student visa expired?</i>

164
00:11:10,936 --> 00:11:14,929
I did not feel right leaving
without paying off my student loans.

165
00:11:15,041 --> 00:11:17,532
- Mm-hmm.
- So I took a job at the Kwik-E-Mart.

166
00:11:17,643 --> 00:11:21,170
When my debts were wiped clean,
I was all set to go.

167
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:24,477
But by then I had made
so many friends here.

168
00:11:24,583 --> 00:11:27,552
What you're saying
is so understandable.

169
00:11:27,653 --> 00:11:30,520
And, really, your only crime
was violating U.S. law.

170
00:11:30,623 --> 00:11:33,091
Oh, you are
one of the good ones.

171
00:11:33,192 --> 00:11:35,888
You know what?
I'm going to vote no on 24.

172
00:11:35,995 --> 00:11:37,492
Mom, you're the greatest!

173
00:11:43,269 --> 00:11:45,237
Could I have this licorice?

174
00:11:46,272 --> 00:11:50,572
Uh, good evening, um, young man.
My name is Charles Norwood.

175
00:11:50,676 --> 00:11:55,909
Furthermore, to this beer, I would also like
three of your finest, cheapest cigars.

176
00:11:56,015 --> 00:11:59,075
Here's my I.D.
which confirms my "adultivity. "

177
00:12:01,987 --> 00:12:03,716
Hmm.

178
00:12:03,823 --> 00:12:07,020
Hey, Kearney, this fake I.D.,
it is truly excellent.

179
00:12:09,128 --> 00:12:12,063
Say, if you tell me
where you obtained it...

180
00:12:12,164 --> 00:12:16,191
I will overlook the ice cream sandwiches
concealed in your armpits, eh?

181
00:12:16,302 --> 00:12:18,099
Deal.

182
00:12:22,875 --> 00:12:28,245
Okay. Here are your fraudulent documents,
Mr. Nahasapeemapetilon.

183
00:12:28,347 --> 00:12:30,747
Your U.S. passport,
social security card...

184
00:12:30,850 --> 00:12:33,410
birth certificate,
and your death certificate.

185
00:12:33,519 --> 00:12:36,716
Just hold onto that one
in your safe-deposit box.

186
00:12:36,822 --> 00:12:39,347
Most humble and
grateful thanks to you.

187
00:12:39,458 --> 00:12:41,358
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa.

188
00:12:41,460 --> 00:12:43,860
Can the courtesy.
You're an American now.

189
00:12:43,963 --> 00:12:46,955
Remember. You were born
in Green Bay, Wisconsin.

190
00:12:47,066 --> 00:12:50,832
Your parents were Herb and
Judy Nahasapeemapetilon.

191
00:12:50,936 --> 00:12:56,272
And if you do not wish to arouse suspicion,
I strongly urge you to act American.

192
00:12:58,010 --> 00:13:01,002
<i>Hey there, Homer. How's it hanging?</i>

193
00:13:01,113 --> 00:13:03,343
Low and lazy. So-

194
00:13:04,950 --> 00:13:07,180
Hey. Say something again.

195
00:13:07,286 --> 00:13:11,222
Oh, you're just noticing the way
I'm talking to you now.

196
00:13:11,323 --> 00:13:15,692
You see, it turns out
I am an American citizen after all.

197
00:13:15,795 --> 00:13:20,459
Apparently, I just plumb forgot about it.

198
00:13:20,566 --> 00:13:25,697
Say, let's take a relaxed attitude
toward work and watch the baseball match.

199
00:13:25,805 --> 00:13:29,707
The "Ny" Mets are
my favorite squadron.

200
00:13:29,809 --> 00:13:32,505
Hey, you got rid of that
goofy sacred elephant statue.

201
00:13:32,611 --> 00:13:36,308
Oh, yeah. What was
I thinking with that?

202
00:13:36,415 --> 00:13:40,681
Who needs the infinite
compassion of Ganesha...

203
00:13:40,786 --> 00:13:45,052
when I've got Tom Cruise
and Nicole Kidman staring at me...

204
00:13:45,157 --> 00:13:47,887
<i>from Entertainment Weekly
with their dead eyes?</i>

205
00:13:47,993 --> 00:13:51,690
Look at me! I've betrayed
my Indian heritage, sir!

206
00:13:51,797 --> 00:13:54,197
What would my parents
think of me now?

207
00:13:57,469 --> 00:14:01,064
Make us proud, Son.
- Never forget who you are.

208
00:14:01,173 --> 00:14:03,869
Don't make the same mistake I did.

209
00:14:03,976 --> 00:14:06,444
Oh, forgive me, Mother.

210
00:14:06,545 --> 00:14:10,743
Father, I've failed you.

211
00:14:17,022 --> 00:14:19,718
Who am I kidding?
I am no citizen.

212
00:14:19,825 --> 00:14:22,555
This passport is a cheap forgery!

213
00:14:22,661 --> 00:14:26,324
A cheap, $2,000 forgery.

214
00:14:26,432 --> 00:14:30,095
I have brought shame to my parents,
to my homeland and to myself.

215
00:14:30,202 --> 00:14:32,295
Don't forget Ganesha.

216
00:14:34,440 --> 00:14:37,739
I cannot deny my roots,
and I cannot keep up this charade.

217
00:14:37,843 --> 00:14:40,676
I only did it because I love this land...

218
00:14:40,779 --> 00:14:45,011
where I have the freedom to say
and to think and to charge whatever I want.

219
00:14:45,117 --> 00:14:47,779
I want to stay, but as the real me...

220
00:14:47,887 --> 00:14:50,412
not as some yahoo from Green Bay.

221
00:14:52,658 --> 00:14:55,422
Oh.

222
00:14:55,527 --> 00:14:57,518
Wow.

223
00:14:57,630 --> 00:15:02,090
You must love this country more than I love
a cold beer on a hot Christmas morning.

224
00:15:02,201 --> 00:15:06,137
Darn it, Apu! I'm not
gonna let them kick you out!

225
00:15:06,238 --> 00:15:09,366
I never should've bought this button!

226
00:15:09,475 --> 00:15:12,467
- Can I have my three dollars back?
- Store credit only.

227
00:15:14,647 --> 00:15:16,842
<i>Hey, Marge.!
Look who I brought home.!</i>

228
00:15:18,183 --> 00:15:21,152
Oh, Homer. Are you
rounding up immigrants?

229
00:15:21,253 --> 00:15:23,380
No, Marge.

230
00:15:23,489 --> 00:15:26,720
Apu convinced me that
Proposition 24 is a big mistake.

231
00:15:26,825 --> 00:15:30,158
All right! Now you've got
all the Simpsons behind you, Apu.

232
00:15:30,262 --> 00:15:33,720
That's nice, although three of you
are below voting age.

233
00:15:33,832 --> 00:15:35,459
And I'm not registered.

234
00:15:35,567 --> 00:15:38,934
I do appreciate your concern, really.
But it is hopeless.

235
00:15:39,038 --> 00:15:43,600
The latest poll shows a whooping
85% support for Proposition 24.

236
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:46,701
<i>Hey, Apu, why don't you just
marry some American broad...</i>

237
00:15:46,812 --> 00:15:49,076
then dump her after
you get your citizenship?

238
00:15:50,382 --> 00:15:53,215
Hello, Selma?

239
00:15:53,319 --> 00:15:55,219
Selma, my dear. How are ya?

240
00:15:55,321 --> 00:15:57,812
Uh-huh. Uh-huh. Uh-huh.

241
00:15:57,923 --> 00:15:59,823
Listen, shut up for a second.

242
00:15:59,925 --> 00:16:02,291
How would you like to marry Apu
so he doesn't get deported?

243
00:16:02,394 --> 00:16:07,195
I'd rather eat poison. My name's already
Selma Bouvier Terwilliger Hutz McClure.

244
00:16:07,299 --> 00:16:10,632
God knows it's long enough
without Nahassapetapeeta-whatever.

245
00:16:10,736 --> 00:16:15,901
From now on, I'm only marrying for love.
Possibly once more for money.

246
00:16:19,611 --> 00:16:22,580
Oh, it's hopeless.
Oh, poor Apu.

247
00:16:22,681 --> 00:16:25,548
Hey! The government
don't control the sky.

248
00:16:25,651 --> 00:16:28,518
<i>- What if you lived in a balloon?
- That's it.!</i>

249
00:16:28,620 --> 00:16:30,588
Did you hear that, Mom?
She's as dumb as me.

250
00:16:30,689 --> 00:16:33,886
No! Not what he said,
what he is.

251
00:16:33,993 --> 00:16:37,451
Grandfather,
as in grandfather clause.

252
00:16:37,563 --> 00:16:41,431
- Apu, how long ago did your visa expire?
- Seven years. But I don't-

253
00:16:41,533 --> 00:16:44,900
There was an amnesty declared
for people who have been here as long as you.

254
00:16:45,004 --> 00:16:47,302
That means you can take
the citizenship test!

255
00:16:47,406 --> 00:16:52,070
- Oh!
- But, Apu, the vote on Proposition 24 is on Tuesday.

256
00:16:52,177 --> 00:16:54,236
You'll have to pass
the test before then.

257
00:16:54,346 --> 00:16:58,180
Oh, no. That is not nearly enough time to
learn over 200 years of American history.

258
00:16:58,283 --> 00:17:00,774
<i>Oh, it can't be that many.</i>

259
00:17:00,886 --> 00:17:03,514
<i>Come on, Apu.
I'll be your tutor.</i>

260
00:17:08,227 --> 00:17:10,422
Please identify this object.

261
00:17:10,529 --> 00:17:14,260
It appears to be the flag which disappeared
from the public library last year.

262
00:17:14,366 --> 00:17:18,598
Correct. Now, we all know
the 13 stripes are for good luck.

263
00:17:18,704 --> 00:17:23,107
But why does the American flag
have precisely 47 stars?

264
00:17:23,208 --> 00:17:26,439
Because this particular flag
is ridiculously out-of-date.

265
00:17:26,545 --> 00:17:30,208
The library must have purchased it
during the brief period in 1912...

266
00:17:30,315 --> 00:17:33,284
after New Mexico became a state,
but before Arizona did.

267
00:17:33,385 --> 00:17:35,216
Uh, partial credit.

268
00:17:37,122 --> 00:17:41,081
Now, they may ask you to locate your town
on a map of the U.S. So, let's do that.

269
00:17:41,193 --> 00:17:44,959
Uh, Springfield, Springfield.
Right here.

270
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:49,592
<i>Dad, you're not pointing anywhere
near Springfield. It's over here, Apu.</i>

271
00:17:49,701 --> 00:17:51,601
Hey! What you doin'? Studyin'?

272
00:17:51,703 --> 00:17:55,730
Oh, I'm so confused. I don't even know
where I'm getting kicked out of anymore.

273
00:18:02,214 --> 00:18:04,114
Whoa!

274
00:18:05,350 --> 00:18:07,250
Sign's floating away, Chief.

275
00:18:07,352 --> 00:18:11,220
Executive, legislative and, uh, judicial.

276
00:18:11,323 --> 00:18:13,951
No, no and no.

277
00:18:14,059 --> 00:18:17,119
Maybe we should start all over
with the electrical college.

278
00:18:17,229 --> 00:18:19,424
Please, Mr. Simpson.
My brain needs sleep.

279
00:18:19,531 --> 00:18:21,431
The test is in six hours.

280
00:18:21,533 --> 00:18:24,001
And many of these facts you speak of
are completely new to me.

281
00:18:24,103 --> 00:18:26,663
Sleep is for the weak, Apu!
Now, I'm gonna go to bed...

282
00:18:26,772 --> 00:18:29,605
while you look over my notes
from ninth-grade history.

283
00:18:29,708 --> 00:18:33,371
Okay, Apu. Stay awake
and stay focused.

284
00:18:33,479 --> 00:18:36,642
Cotton Mather-

285
00:18:40,986 --> 00:18:43,181
Oh, no! I fell asleep!

286
00:18:43,288 --> 00:18:46,223
I have forgotten everything
that Mr. Homer taught me!

287
00:18:46,325 --> 00:18:48,816
Perfect. Let's roll.

288
00:18:51,296 --> 00:18:55,027
Immigrant go home!
Immigrant go home!

289
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:57,193
- Get outta here!
- Gosh, you're annoying.

290
00:19:00,172 --> 00:19:02,072
Hmm. Hmph.

291
00:19:03,709 --> 00:19:05,609
Hmm.

292
00:19:09,781 --> 00:19:12,511
All right, men.
Here's the order of deportations.

293
00:19:12,618 --> 00:19:16,748
First you'll be rounding up
your tired, then your poor...

294
00:19:16,855 --> 00:19:19,688
then your huddled masses
yearning to breathe free.

295
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:21,258
Breathers. Got it.

296
00:19:21,360 --> 00:19:23,123
All right,
here's your last question.

297
00:19:23,228 --> 00:19:25,423
What was the cause
of the Civil War?

298
00:19:25,531 --> 00:19:27,658
Actually,
there were numerous causes.

299
00:19:27,766 --> 00:19:31,759
Aside from the obvious schism between
abolitionists and anti-abolitionists...

300
00:19:31,870 --> 00:19:34,532
economic factors,
both domestic and international-

301
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:35,607
- Hey, hey!
- Yeah?

302
00:19:35,707 --> 00:19:38,471
- Just say slavery.
- Slavery it is, sir.

303
00:19:39,645 --> 00:19:42,273
Yes! I am a citizen!

304
00:19:42,381 --> 00:19:44,474
Now, which way
to the welfare office?

305
00:19:44,583 --> 00:19:48,019
- What?
- I'm kidding. I'm kidding. I work. I work.

306
00:19:49,321 --> 00:19:52,256
<i>Thank you.
I want to say thank you to everyone.</i>

307
00:19:52,357 --> 00:19:56,157
From this day forth, I am no longer
an Indian living in America.

308
00:19:56,261 --> 00:19:58,593
I am an Indian American.

309
00:19:58,697 --> 00:20:01,165
Yeah!

310
00:20:01,266 --> 00:20:04,326
You know, Apu, in a way,
all Americans are immigrants.

311
00:20:04,436 --> 00:20:06,336
Except Native Americans.

312
00:20:06,438 --> 00:20:08,338
Yeah. Native Americans
like us.

313
00:20:08,440 --> 00:20:10,340
- No. I mean American Indians.
- Like me.

314
00:20:10,442 --> 00:20:11,909
No. I mean-

315
00:20:12,010 --> 00:20:15,070
Hi, everyone. If I could
just say a few words...

316
00:20:15,180 --> 00:20:17,080
I'd be a better public speaker.

317
00:20:19,117 --> 00:20:21,483
Now that you're all relaxed-

318
00:20:21,587 --> 00:20:24,488
Most of us here
were born in America.

319
00:20:24,590 --> 00:20:26,854
We take this country
for granted.

320
00:20:26,959 --> 00:20:28,859
But not immigrants like Apu.

321
00:20:28,961 --> 00:20:31,361
While the rest of us are
drinking ourselves stupid...

322
00:20:31,463 --> 00:20:34,455
they're driving the cabs
that get us home safely...

323
00:20:34,566 --> 00:20:37,364
they're writing the operas
that entertain us every day...

324
00:20:37,469 --> 00:20:40,563
they're training our tigers
and kicking our extra points.

325
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:46,110
These people are the glue that
holds together the gears of our society.

326
00:20:46,211 --> 00:20:51,308
If we pass Proposition 24, we'll be losing
some of the truest Americans of all.

327
00:20:53,418 --> 00:20:55,352
When you go to the polls tomorrow...

328
00:20:55,454 --> 00:20:59,356
please vote no on Proposition 24.

329
00:20:59,458 --> 00:21:02,154
No on 24.

330
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:04,729
No on 24.

331
00:21:04,830 --> 00:21:07,458
No on 24.

332
00:21:07,566 --> 00:21:12,970
<i>No on 24. No on 24.</i>

333
00:21:13,071 --> 00:21:15,631
<i>No on 24.</i>

334
00:21:15,741 --> 00:21:18,369
<i>No on 24.</i>

335
00:21:19,478 --> 00:21:22,743
It's a landslide! Yes on 24.

336
00:21:22,848 --> 00:21:26,716
The proposition
passed with a record 95%.

337
00:21:26,818 --> 00:21:31,778
When are people going to learn?
Democracy doesn't work!

338
00:21:31,890 --> 00:21:33,824
Please don't knock
the land that I love.

339
00:21:34,926 --> 00:21:37,759
Jury duty!

340
00:21:37,863 --> 00:21:41,594
Oh! Today I am truly
an American citizen.

341
00:21:46,338 --> 00:21:50,206
Just thank heaven everything worked out
for the people we care about.

342
00:21:51,510 --> 00:21:55,276
Ach! Ingrates.

343
00:22:42,094 --> 00:22:44,062
Shh!

